               <head>Akbarnamah, daftar 2</head>
               <msContents>
                  <summary>1 copy of Akbarnāmah by Shaykh Abū al-Faẓl ibn Shaykh Mubārak Nāgawrī</summary>
                  <msItem class="http://lccn.loc.gov/n80002413 http://lccn.loc.gov/sh2008115921 http://lccn.loc.gov/sh2008115920" n="1" xml:id="Uk_IO_Islamic_3917-item1">
                     <author>
                        <persName xml:lang="per-Latn-x-lc" type="supplied" key="ark:/81055/vdc_100164658503.0x000001 viaf_5150639">Shaykh Abū al-Faẓl ibn Shaykh Mubārak Nāgawrī</persName>
                        <persName xml:lang="per" key="ark:/81055/vdc_100164658503.0x000001 viaf_5150639" type="supplied">شيخ ابو الفضل ابن شيخ مبارك ناگورى</persName>
                     </author>
                     <title xml:lang="per-Latn-x-lc" key="work_20880">Akbarnāmah</title>
                     <title xml:lang="per" key="work_20880">اكبر نامه</title>
                     <note>
                        <p>Official regnal <term xml:lang="en">chronicle</term> for the reign of the Mughal Emperor  <persName xml:lang="per-Latn-x-lc" key="ark:/81055/vdc_100164657160.0x000001 viaf_3264079" role="subject">Akbar (1542-1605)</persName>
                        </p>
                        <p>Comprises the second <term xml:lang="per-Latn-x-lc">daftar</term> only
                        </p>
                        <p>Defective at both ends</p>
                        <p>Not dated</p>
                        <p>Note (dated <date calendar="Gregorian">26 May 1904</date>) from <persName xml:lang="per-Latn-x-lc" key="viaf_42076979" role="ann">H. Beveridge</persName> to <persName xml:lang="per-Latn-x-lc" key="viaf_8170991" role="fmo">W. Irvine</persName> attached to <term xml:lang="en">flyleaf</term>: "I return you your two MSS. and Malet with many thanks. Your <term xml:lang="per-Latn-x-lc">Akbarnama</term> is a good copy of the latter part of the book, but there is nothing special about it. The marginal words are merely the filling up of lacunae. There are no notes, &amp; so far as I can see, no readings different from those in common use. The Bib. Ind. (<term xml:lang="en">Bibliotheca Indica</term>) is not a good edition &amp; is often very bad about names of places &amp; persons, &amp; in respect of these your copy is commonly better than the Bib. Ind."
                        </p>
                     </note>
                     <textLang mainLang="per" xml:lang="per">Persian</textLang>
                     <note/>
                  </msItem>
